.TH CT 1 "March 2026" "ct 4.3.0" "User Commands"

.SH NAME
ct \- trace Bash command resolution and detect command conflicts

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ct
[\fIoptions\fR] \fIcommand\fR
.br
.B ct
.B \-c
[\fIoptions\fR]

.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBct\fR (Command Trace) analyzes how Bash resolves a command name and what executable the kernel ultimately runs.

It traces the full Bash command resolution process, including aliases,
functions, keywords, builtins, and external executables. It reports
shadowing, overrides, and filesystem indirection such as symlinks,
alternatives, and usr-merged directory layouts.

The command argument must be a bare command name. Paths such as
\fI/bin/ls\fR or \fI./script\fR are rejected.

When invoked with \fB\-c\fR, \fBct\fR performs environment-wide conflict
analysis instead of tracing a single command.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Display usage information and exit.

.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-version
Display version and license information and exit.

.TP
.BR \-j ", " \-\-json
Emit structured JSON output suitable for scripting and automation.

Notes:
.IP
Fields may be added in future versions.
.br
Schema stability is not guaranteed.
.br
\fInull\fR indicates “not applicable.”
.br
Boolean values are always \fItrue\fR or \fIfalse\fR.

.TP
.BR \-x ", " \-\-extend
Manually extend \fB$PATH\fR to include common system and admin directories during resolution.
.br
The original environment is restored on exit, even on failure.

.TP
.BR \-c ", " \-\-conflict
Run environment-wide command conflict analysis.

.SH CONFLICT MODE
In \fB\-c\fR mode, \fBct\fR scans shell-defined command namespaces:

.IP
keywords
.br
aliases
.br
functions
.br
builtins

Only shell-defined symbols are considered.

External executables in \fB$PATH\fR are not part of resolution logic.
They are only checked for presence and reported as indicators (e.g. external(shadowed)).

Each name is evaluated against Bash resolution rules to determine:
.IP
definition sources
.br
precedence
.br
shadowed (unreachable) definitions

This mode is intended for detecting naming collisions in shell environments.

.SH LIMITATIONS
.IP
Only bare command names are accepted.
.br
Behavior depends on the current shell environment.
.br
Filesystem inspection may vary by platform and permissions.
.br
Conflict analysis may be slow in large or heavily customized environments.
.br
PATH-based executable resolution is excluded from conflict analysis by design.

.SH REQUIREMENTS
Bash ≥ 4.4
.br
GNU/Linux
.br
coreutils: grep, file, cut, head, readlink, readelf, awk

.SH ENVIRONMENT
\fBct\fR temporarily modifies shell state during execution:

.IP
\fB$PATH\fR may be extended and restored automatically.
.br
\fBextglob\fR may be enabled temporarily.
.br
No permanent environment changes are made.

\fBct\fR does not enforce strict shell error modes (\fBset -euo pipefail\fR); non-zero exit codes are part of normal operation.

